Class SinkCursor<I>

Type Parameters:
I -
All Implemented Interfaces:
Iterator<I>, Cursor<I>, Node, Sink<I>, MetaDataManageable<Object,Object>, MetaDataProvider<CompositeMetaData<Object,Object>>
public class SinkCursor<I>
extends AbstractSink<I>
implements Cursor<I>

Sink component in a query graph that provides an iteration over the elements streaming in. A Queue is used to buffer the elements coming in, which is implemented in XXL as an iterator. Therefore a demand-driven processing is enabled.
This class realizes the design pattern Adapter.

Intent:
"Convert the interface of a class into another interface clients expect. Adapter lets classes work together that couldn't otherwise because of incompatible interfaces."
For further information see: "Gamma et al.: DesignPatterns. Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software. Addision Wesley 1998."

Example usage (1): 

        Enumerator e = new Enumerator(10, 200);
        SinkCursor cursor =  new SinkCursor(e, new ListQueue());
        try {
                while(cursor.hasNext()){
                        System.out.println(cursor.next());
                        Thread.currentThread().sleep(190);
                }
        }
        catch (InterruptedException ex) {
                System.err.println("ERROR : "+ex.getMessage());
                ex.printStackTrace(System.err);
        }

Since:
1.1
See Also:
Cursor, Queue

hasNext

public boolean hasNext()
Returns true if the iteration has more elements. (In other words, returns true if next or peek would return an element rather than throwing an exception.)
This operation is implemented idempotent, i.e., consequent calls to hasNext() do not have any effect.
Locks, if the buffer contains an element. Otherwise, the thread this cursor belongs to has to wait until new elements are buffered. Except the sink received a done call, then the buffer is closed until all its elements have been processed.

Specified by:
hasNext in interface Iterator<I>
Specified by:
hasNext in interface Cursor<I>
Returns:
true if the cursor has more elements.

open

public void open()
Description copied from interface: Cursor
Opens the cursor, i.e., signals the cursor to reserve resources, open files, etc. Before a cursor has been opened calls to methods like next or peek are not guaranteed to yield proper results. Therefore open must be called before a cursor's data can be processed. Multiple calls to open do not have any effect, i.e., if open was called the cursor remains in the state opened until its close method is called.

Note, that a call to the open method of a closed cursor usually does not open it again because of the fact that its state generally cannot be restored when resources are released respectively files are closed.

Specified by:
open in interface Cursor<I>
